data.content:
Here is the full performance analysis of `StringReadability.cs`, a confirmed hot path called on every user-facing string in a CMS.

---

## Scan Execution Checklist

| Recipe | Hits |
|--------|------|
| `.ToLower()/.ToUpper()` without culture | **3** (L97, L103, L106) |
| `.All()/.Any()` LINQ | **2** (L93, L101) |
| `.Select/.Cast/.Aggregate` LINQ | **4** (L88, L89, L171, L214) |
| `.Replace(` | **1** (L187) |
| `params` in signatures | **1** (L213) |
| `string[1..]` slice | **2** (L106, L132) |
| `RegexOptions.Compiled` | 2 (behind `#else` for <.NET 7 ✅) |
| `GeneratedRegex` | 2 (behind `#if NET7_0_OR_GREATER` ✅) |
| Unsealed classes | **3 of 3** (0% sealed) |
| `.Substring`, `.IndexOf(string)`, `.Contains(string)` | 0 each |

---

## Findings

### 🔴 1. Compound LINQ chain in `FromPascalCase` — ~10+ allocations per call (1 instance)

**Impact:** Called on every non-underscore/dash string via `Humanize()`. Per invocation: MatchCollection + `.Cast<Match>()` enumerator + `.Select()` enumerator + delegate + N × (CharEnumerator from `.All()` + `.ToLower()` string). For a 3-word PascalCase input, ~10+ allocations per call × hundreds of strings = massive GC pressure.

**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L86-98`

**Fix:** Replace LINQ chain with `foreach` over `MatchCollection` and `StringBuilder`:

```csharp
internal static string FromPascalCase(string input)
{
    var matches = PascalCaseWordPartsRegex().Matches(input);
    if (matches.Count == 0)
        return input;

    var sb = new StringBuilder(input.Length + matches.Count);
    for (int i = 0; i < matches.Count; i++)
    {
        if (i > 0) sb.Append(' ');
        var match = matches[i];
        var value = match.ValueSpan; // zero-alloc on .NET 7+

        if (IsAllUpper(value) &&
            (value.Length > 1 || (match.Index > 0 && input[match.Index - 1] == ' ')
             || value is "I"))
        {
            sb.Append(value);
        }
        else
        {
            foreach (char c in value)
                sb.Append(char.ToLowerInvariant(c));
        }
    }

    // Check all-upper result
    bool allUpper = true;
    bool hasSpace = false;
    foreach (char c in sb.ToString())
    {
        if (c == ' ') hasSpace = true;
        else if (!char.IsUpper(c)) { allUpper = false; break; }
    }

    string result = sb.ToString();
    if (allUpper && hasSpace)
        result = result.ToLowerInvariant();

    return result.Length > 0
        ? Concat(char.ToUpperInvariant(result[0]), result.AsSpan(1))
        : result;
}

private static bool IsAllUpper(ReadOnlySpan<char> span)
{
    foreach (char c in span)
        if (!char.IsUpper(c)) return false;
    return span.Length > 0;
}
```

### 🔴 2. `Dehumanize` double-humanizes every word — 2x redundant processing (1 instance)

**Impact:** `Dehumanize` calls `word.Humanize().Pascalize()` per word, but `Pascalize()` internally calls `.Humanize()` *again*. Every word is regex-processed twice. For N words: 2N regex evaluations + 2N LINQ chains + N `params` arrays + N `.Replace()` allocations.

**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L171, L187`

**Fix:** Either have `Pascalize` accept already-humanized input, or inline the title-casing logic in `Dehumanize`:

```csharp
public static string Dehumanize(this string input)
{
    var words = input.Split(' ', StringSplitOptions.RemoveEmptyEntries);
    if (words.Length == 0) return input;
    if (words.Length == 1) return words[0].Humanize().Pascalize();

    var sb = new StringBuilder(input.Length);
    foreach (var word in words)
    {
        var humanized = word.Humanize();
        if (humanized.Length > 0)
        {
            sb.Append(char.ToUpperInvariant(humanized[0]));
            sb.Append(humanized.AsSpan(1));
        }
    }
    return sb.ToString();
}
```

### 🟡 3. `.ToLower()` culture-sensitive + allocating (3 instances)

**Impact:** `.ToLower()` is culture-sensitive (incorrect for machine identifiers) and allocates a new string. Called per-match in the LINQ lambda = N allocations per `FromPascalCase` call.

**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L97, L103, L106`

**Fix:** Use `char.ToLowerInvariant()` per-char in a span/StringBuilder (eliminated by Finding 1 fix), or `ToLowerInvariant()` at minimum for L103.

### 🟡 4. LINQ `.All()` on `string` — allocates CharEnumerator (2 instances)

**Impact:** `string` implements `IEnumerable<char>`, so `.All()` allocates a `CharEnumerator` + delegate. Called per-match (L93) and per-result (L101).

**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L93, L101`

**Fix:** Replace with `foreach` or span-based loop (eliminated by Finding 1 fix with `IsAllUpper` helper).

### 🟡 5. `result[1..]` string slice + concatenation — 2 allocations (1 instance)

**Impact:** `char.ToUpper(result[0]) + result[1..]` allocates a substring from `[1..]`, then concatenates with `+` for another allocation. The existing `Concat(char, ReadOnlySpan<char>)` helper at L128 already avoids this.

**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L106`

**Fix:** `Concat(char.ToUpperInvariant(result[0]), result.AsSpan(1))` — uses the existing helper, 1 allocation instead of 2.

### 🟡 6. `params IStringTransformer[]` allocates array per call (1 instance)

**Impact:** Every `.Transform(To.TitleCase)` call allocates a 1-element `IStringTransformer[]`. On this hot path, that's one array per `Pascalize()` call.

**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L213`

**Fix:** Add a 1-arg overload to avoid the array:

```csharp
public static string Transform(this string input, IStringTransformer transformer) =>
    transformer.Transform(input);
```

### 🟡 7. `Pascalize` chains 3 allocating calls (1 instance)

**Impact:** `input.Humanize().Transform(To.TitleCase).Replace(" ", "")` creates 3 intermediate strings plus a `params` array. Each call to `Pascalize` triggers a full `Humanize` regex pipeline.

**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L187`

**Fix:** Inline the pascalization logic to avoid re-humanizing and intermediate strings (addressed by Finding 2 fix).

### ℹ️ 8. Unsealed `IStringTransformer` classes — 3 of 3 unsealed (0%)

**Impact:** `ToTitleCase`, `ToLowerCase`, `ToUpperCase` are all internal leaf classes implementing `IStringTransformer`. Sealing enables JIT devirtualization of `.Transform()` calls.

**Files:** `StringReadability.cs:L226, L232, L237`

**Fix:** Add `sealed` keyword: `internal sealed class ToTitleCase`, etc.

---

## Positive Findings

- ✅ **`[GeneratedRegex]` with `#if` fallback** — correctly uses source-gen on .NET 7+ with compiled fallback (L12-27)
- ✅ **`Concat(char, ReadOnlySpan<char>)` uses `stackalloc`** — efficient span-based concat (L130-133)
- ✅ **`Concat(ReadOnlySpan<char>, ReadOnlySpan<char>)` uses `string.Concat`** — correct span API (L119)
- ✅ **`IStringTransformer` singletons cached as static properties** — no per-call allocation (L217-223)

---

## Summary

| Severity | Count | Top Issue |
|----------|-------|-----------|
| 🔴 Critical | 2 | LINQ chain in `FromPascalCase` (~10+ allocs/call); `Dehumanize` double-processes every word |
| 🟡 Moderate | 4 | `.ToLower()` culture + alloc; LINQ `.All()` on string; `[1..]` slice; `params` array |
| ℹ️ Info | 1 | 3 unsealed leaf classes |

**Estimated per-call allocation reduction:** Fixing findings 1-2 alone would eliminate **~20-30 allocations per `Humanize`/`Dehumanize` call**. At hundreds of dynamic strings per page render, this is thousands of avoidable allocations per request.

> ⚠️ **Disclaimer:** These results are generated by an AI assistant and are non-deterministic. Findings may include false positives, miss real issues, or suggest changes that are incorrect for your specific context. Always verify recommendations with benchmarks and human review before applying changes to production code.
